We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations, with modification, for the Local Chief Executive to:

Require the GSO to:

Follow the procedures for the disposition of non-existing/missing PPEs provided under Paragraph 7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Conduct the disposal of the unserviceable PPEs according to the rules and regulations outlined in Rules 21 to 29 of COA Circular No. 92-386 for the disposal of unserviceable supplies or property, while awaiting the release of the DBM-COA Joint Circular on the Revised Manual on Disposal of Government Property;
After disposal, submit the IIRUP and IIRUSP for disposed items to the Accounting Unit for recording in the books of accounts; and
Include the Land Improvement, Infrastructure Assets, Buildings and Other Structures, Military Equipment, and Sports Equipment in the physical count.
Require the Accounting Office to:

Take up the necessary accounting entries to recognize PPEs found at station, loss of PPEs; set up the corresponding receivables from the concerned accountable personnel of the missing PPEs after failure to present the missing PPEs despite demand, or failure to pay the depreciated replacement cost; drop from the books of accounts the unserviceable properties based on IIRUP and IIRUSP and after disposal;
Reclassify items costing ₱50,000.00 below and comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2022-004;
Conduct thorough reconciliation of account balances reported in the Trial Balance and Lapsing Schedule; and
Prepare Lapsing Schedule for Military, Police and Security Equipment and Books under the General Fund.
Require the accountable personnel for the missing PPEs to respond to the demand letter and produce the missing PPEs or pay the depreciated replacement cost of the same, or to request for Relief from Accountability in accordance with 2009 Revised Rules of Procedure of COA and Key Procedural Flow (Appendix “J” of this AAR) upon satisfaction of the conditions listed therein.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive and other officials shall:

a. Strictly observe the provisions set forth under COA Circular No. 2012-003 to safeguard the government funds against loss or wastage through illegal or improper disposition, intending to ensure efficiency, economy, and effectiveness in the operations of government, otherwise, a notice of disallowance will be issued;

b. Require the City Accountant to demand the return/payment from the concerned employees who were payees/recipients and liable for the excessive traveling expenses, meals, airfare expenses, and per diem totaling ₱91,973.36 incurred during CDPC; otherwise, a notice of disallowance will be issued;

a. Revisit the created Inventory Committee and direct the said committee to avail of One-Time Cleansing of its PPEs as provided under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
b. Designate a General Service Officer (GSO) to take custody of and be responsible for all properties of the Municipality and direct him/her to:
 o Maintain Property Cards (PC) for the PPEs to account for the receipt and disposition;
 o Assign property number for each PPE item (Property Sticker);
 o Prepare a separate report on unserviceable properties, plant and equipment and facilitate the preparation of Inspection and Inventory Report; 
 o Update the property records based on the results of the physical inventory and reconcile with accounting records to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts to be considered as the correct balance of the agency's PPEs; and
 o Ensure the Municipal Building as required under Republic Act No. 6556 dated September 1, 1951 as amended by PD No. 245 dated July 13, 1973.
c. Require the Municipal Accountant to:
 o Maintain PPE Ledger Card for each category of asset;
 o Prepare the necessary adjustments on the deficiencies noted based on the result of the actual inventory taking; and
 o Make reconciliation with inventory reports, property cards, and subsidiary ledgers.
d. Furnish the COA Audit Team with a copy of the Updated Inventory Report and/ or Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, and Equipment (RPCPPE).

a. Ensure that the Municipal Engineer has provided the local accountant and the general services officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
b. Direct the Supply Officer/ GSO to maintain the Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Cards for each local road and its components and reconcile the total amount of local roads recognized in the Report on Local Road Network with that of the total amount presented in the FS;
c. Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct an annual physical count of the road networks and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Local Road Networks; and
d. Require the Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the total road network system following the format provided in Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-008 and reconcile the total amount of local roads presented in the FS with the records of the Supply Officer/ GSO.

Require the Municipal Planning and Development Officer and Municipal Engineer the following:
a. Ensure timely implementation of all 20% development projects;
b. Keep track with the BAC Chairman of procurement schedules of development projects;
c. Review and assess the unimplemented projects/unobligated funds especially those from previous years and consider the possibility of proposing to the Municipal Development Council (MDC) the re-appropriation/realignment of the unutilized funds to other priority development projects; and
d. Conduct regular monitoring and evaluation of the projects and respond to the causes of delays in the actual implementation.

