We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to ascertain that payments of fuel are duly supported with properly filled out driver’s trip tickets for proper evaluation on the propriety and reasonableness of fuel consumption;

Direct the vehicle drivers to secure an authority before any trip is undertaken and to properly accomplish the driver’s trip ticket i.e. vehicle plate number, time of departure and arrival of the trip, place of destination, purpose of travel, distance travelled et.al.; 

Require the driver of each motor vehicle of the Municipality to prepare at the end of each month, a Monthly Report of Official Travels summarizing in chronological order the trips for the month certified by the driver and approved by the Administrative Officer; 

Require the personnel concerned to prepare and submit monthly the Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption to the Auditor showing among others, the different types of motor vehicles utilized by the Municipality during the month, total distance travelled, total fuel used and the fuel consumption for each vehicle; and

Submit a justification for various travels undertaken on the same day by the same driver, otherwise such fuel charges will be disallowed in audit.

We recommended that:

The Municipal Mayor and other Municipal officials adopt austerity measures to avoid incurrence of overdraft in its future operations;
The Municipal Treasurer observe strictly Section 337 of the Local Government Code regarding restrictions upon limit of disbursements to avoid incurrence of cash overdraft;

The Municipality avoid the utilization of withheld amounts from the salaries of its officials and employees, fund transfers and trust liabilities for DRRMF for other obligations other than its intended purpose/s; and

The Municipal officials who certified and approved the disbursements with insufficient cash shall be liable for the incurrence of cash overdraft/deficit.

We recommended that the:

The Municipal Mayor, Sangguniang Bayan and the Municipal Treasurer address the existing problem regarding unremitted CY 2013 and prior years GSIS premiums and loan repayments. 

The Municipal Accountant immediately remit all the withheld taxes to the BIR thru its authorized depository bank. Henceforth, she must regularly remit all taxes withheld within 10 days following the end of the month pursuant to Section 2.58 A.2a of BIR Revenue Regulation No. 2-98 dated April 17,1998;

In addition, she must identify employees with prior years’ unremitted premiums under Pag-ibig and Philhealth and unremitted loan amortization under Pag-ibig and remit the same to the concerned corporations without further delay;

The personnel in charge at the Municipal Accounting Office ensure that all current withheld premiums and loan amortizations are remitted based on the prescribed payment schedule of the three corporations to avoid penalty for delayed payment; 

Moreover, he must reconcile amount withheld for premiums and loans with the amount due for remittance under the three corporations before preparing the Disbursement Vouchers (DVs); and

Lastly, the Municipal Accountant book the unrecorded taxes withheld, premiums and loan amortizations deducted from the salaries of officials and employees for the months of January and June 2019.

We recommended that Municipal Mayor:

Direct the Municipal Accountant-designate submit all lacking original vouchers and supporting documents to the Office of the Auditor for the periods January to June 2018;

Require the Municipal Accountant-designate to ensure that submission of vouchers shall strictly follow the procedures prescribed under Section 44 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume 1, Section 107 of   P.D. 1445 and Section 7.2.1 of the Rules and Regulations on the Settlement of Accounts;

Hire a Municipal Accountant and additional accounting personnel to resolve the problem of work overload in the Accounting Office.

